Transcription 

Helicase is an enzyme which cuts the DNA double helix in half by breaking the hydrogen bonds between the purine and
pyrimidine complementary base pairs. One half becomes the template for mRNA. RNA polymerase brings the
complementary pairs in, producing a chain (the mRNA).  

 

Translation 

The mRNA is transported to the ribosome from the nucleus via a vesicle. It attaches itself to the P (central) and A sites of
the ribosome (which has 3 sites in total). The tRNA then brings the complementary base pair and the corresponding
amino acid into the P and A sites, starting with the Start Codon "AUG". The amino acids bind and begin producing a
chain. The mRNA begins moving across the E site, with new complementary codons entering only on the A site. This
continues until the End Codon is reached. The protein is formed from the amino acid chain. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

DNA is built of a series of nucleotides (sugar + phosphate + nitrogenous base [ACGT/U in RNA]). Covalent bonds between
the P and the Sugar hold a single chain together. The two chains of the DNA strand bond with H-bonds. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Making DNA compact 

Histones are a protein which supercoils the DNA to make in compact. 8 histones inside the coil and 1 histone outside to
pin the coil in its shape are used. The structure below coils up, then coils up again… into a supercoil. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Each group of 9 histones and 1 section of DNA is a chromatin. A gene is a section of DNA 3 base pairs long, and alleles
are the variations of a gene. Certain genes are coding regions (exons) whilst certain genes are non-coding (introns).
Introns only exist in DNA and are removed during transcription from the RNA strand. A coding region will produce
proteins whilst a non-coding region will not. Hence only coding regions are expressed.  

 

WTF is a regulatory sequence 

WTF are promoter, enhancer/silencer 

Mitochondrial DNA 

 

RNA polymerase binds to DNA just before the Start Codon, which is the "Promoter" region. 

 

Replication 

Helicase cuts DNA in half. Primase enzyme puts a primer of complementary bases onto one chain. Polymerase III starts
from the primer, producing the complementary strand to the leading strand in a 5' to 3' direction. The lagging strand,
which goes 3' to 5' in the direction of cutting, requires multiple primers and subsequent Okazaki fragments in the 5' to 3'
direction. Endonuclease removes the primers, and polymerase replaces these with DNA, then ligase seals up any fragments in the strand to produce two continuous strands.  

 

Cell differentiation 

Cellular differentiation is the process by which a less specialised cell becomes a more specialised cell type. Different
tissues have different types of cells. Different types of cells possess different active genes, which are regulated by
regulatory sequences. Stem cells can both self-renew and differentiate. They may give rise to progenitor cells which are
like stem cells but do not self-renew.  

 

Totipotent stem cells are capable of giving rise to any human cell, plus extraembryonic or placental cells. These can give
rise to entire functional organisms. Pluripotent stem cells can give rise to all differentiated body cell types, but not to an
entire organism. Multipotent stem cells are undifferentiated cells present in differentiated tissue used to replace
dead/dysfunctional cells. These cells renew themselves or specialise to yield all cell types present in the tissue from
which it originated. 

 

Heredity 

Genotype: the combination of alleles for a gene 

Phenotype: observable traits resulting from a combination of alleles (genotype) 

Eg: Genotype of "ww" produces phenotype of "Straight hairline" 

Epigenetic variability describes the phenotypes that cannot be immediately explained by genes only, usually resulting
from the influence of multiple genes and the environment 

 

Briefly describe how meiosis and recombination contribute to individual uniqueness and genetic variability. 

-One gamete, each containing a different set of DNA, come from each parent to form a zygote 

-Crossing over between Prophase 1 and Metaphase 1 further create genetic variation  

-Mutations 

 

DNA mutations 

-Addition/Deletion: causes a frame shift and potentially significant disease, harmful for offspring 

-Substitution: not that harmful, can be harmful for offspring 

-Inversion: no loss of information, so typically less harmful for the individual but very harmful for offspring 

-Translocation (movement of one chromosome segment to another) and Reciprocal translocation (exchange of chromosome segments) involve no loss of information and thus are like inversion.
